  "messages": [
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Return Run with Walking Breaks\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a slow, flat-footed walk for 2-3 minutes to gently warm up the plantar fascia and calf complex before any running. Focus on relaxed breathing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"Run 4 minutes easy at the top of your easy pace range (6:12/km or slower — comfort over pace today). After each 4-minute run segment, take a 2-minute brisk walk. If you feel any foot discomfort at any point, drop to walking immediately. No heroics here.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"Walk briskly for 2 minutes between each running segment. This isn't rest — it's active recovery that keeps blood flowing to the plantar fascia without overloading it.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish with a 3-minute easy walk. Afterwards, gently roll the sole of your foot on a frozen water bottle for 2-3 minutes if your physio has recommended this.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for 2-3 minutes before you start running. The plantar fascia is stiffest first thing in the morning, so if this is a morning run, give yourself extra time to loosen up. Ankle circles and gentle calf raises off a step (if cleared) can help.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 3 minutes after your final run segment. Sit down and gently flex and extend your foot 10 times. Ice the heel/arch for 10-15 minutes if there was any discomfort during the run — always worth checking in with your physio on your icing protocol.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"James, welcome back. This first session of the week is about re-establishing your running rhythm, not about pace or distance. Your physio has cleared you for 20 minutes of easy running, and we're going to honour that exactly. The run-walk structure gives your plantar fascia a chance to handle load and then recover within the same session — this is a deliberate physiological choice, not a sign that you're not fit enough. Your aerobic base from your 44:00 10K is still largely intact; the goal right now is tissue tolerance, not fitness building. Keep your effort genuinely easy — you should be able to hold a full conversation throughout. If your foot speaks up, listen to it immediately and drop to walking.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Mid-Week Easy Run — Consistency Check\",\"target_distance_km\":3,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 3 minutes. Focus on loosening your ankles and hips. Take note of how your right foot feels before you start running — this is useful data for your physio.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"Same structure as Tuesday: 4 minutes easy running, 2 minutes walking, repeated 3 times. If Tuesday went well with zero foot discomfort, you can aim for a slightly more fluid stride today — but still fully conversational effort. Pace is secondary to comfort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"Walk recovery between run segments. Use this time to check in with your body — scan from foot to knee to hip. Notice, don't judge.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3-minute easy walk to close out. Stretch calves gently — tight calves increase load on the plantar fascia, so keeping them mobile is genuinely therapeutic here.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Same warm-up protocol as Tuesday. If your foot felt stiff or sore on Tuesday or Wednesday, give yourself an extra 5 minutes of walking before you attempt any running today. There is no shame in turning this into a pure walking session if something doesn't feel right.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Calf stretches — both straight-leg (gastrocnemius) and bent-knee (soleus) — are worth building into your post-run routine consistently. The soleus in particular attaches near the plantar fascia and keeping it supple makes a real difference over time.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This mid-week session serves two purposes: building consistency (which is the true currency of a return-to-running plan) and giving you a second data point on how your foot is responding. How Tuesday felt should inform how you approach today. If Tuesday was pain-free and you felt good, this is a confidence-builder. If Tuesday was uncomfortable, today is a chance to dial back and that information is gold for your next physio appointment. Either way, you're doing the right thing by showing up and running smart. No speed work, no pushing — your physio's guidance is the guardrail here and it's a good one.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Saturday Easy Long Run — Building Time on Feet\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with 3 minutes of walking. Saturday runs can feel different to mid-week — take your time. If the foot feels tight, extend the walk to 5 minutes before attempting to run.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":2,\"notes\":\"Two blocks of 5 minutes easy running with a 2-minute walk between them. This is your longest continuous running block of the week. Keep the pace genuinely easy — top of the easy range (6:12/km) or slower. Think of this as a moving meditation, not a workout to push through.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":2,\"notes\":\"Walk recovery. Use this to shake out your legs and check in with your foot. If there's any discomfort building, stop the run here and walk the rest of the time.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of walking. Saturday cooldowns are worth extending — you have the time. This walking period also helps gradually reduce any foot load before you're sedentary for the evening.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk for at least 3 minutes before running. If you're doing this run in the morning, be especially patient — plantar fasciitis is classically worst with the first steps of the day, and a thorough warm-up walk makes a real difference. Consider doing some gentle foot-towel scrunches or marble pickups if your physio has recommended these exercises before loading the foot.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After your 5-minute walk cooldown, take time to ice the heel and arch if there was any discomfort. Elevate your foot for 15-20 minutes if you can. This is also a good day to do any foot-strengthening exercises your physio has prescribed — post-run, once you've cooled down, is often a good time for these.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday is your long run day, and right now 'long' simply means a little more time on your feet than the other two days — not more distance, not more effort. The slight step-up to 5-minute running blocks (from 4-minute blocks earlier in the week) is intentional and modest. You're accumulating a total of around 4km across the week's three runs, which is a meaningful and deliberate increase from your recent 6.1km week — roughly within the 10% progression guideline when we account for the run-walk format and your physio's 20-minute cap. The 5-minute continuous running blocks also give your plantar fascia a slightly longer stimulus to adapt to, which is how tissue remodelling works — graduated load, not avoidance. If this goes well across the week, that's excellent data for your next physio check-in and potentially a conversation about progressing run durations.\",\"perceived_effort\":3}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
